    evergreen: true,
    textContent:
      "R401      \n*Bumpers should protect all corners. Robots are required to use Bumpers\nto protect all outside corners of the Frame Perimeter.\nFor adequate protection, at least 6 in. (~16 cm) of Bumper\nmust be placed on each side of each outside corner (see Figure 9‑3) and\nmust extend to within ¼ in. (~6 mm) of the Frame\nPerimeter corner. If a Frame Perimeter side\nis shorter than 12 in. (~31 cm), that entire FRAME PERIMETER side must be\nprotected by a Bumper (see Figure 9‑4). A\nround or circular Frame Perimeter, or segment\nof the Frame Perimeter, is considered to have\nan infinite number of corners, therefore the entire frame or frame segment must\nbe completely protected by Bumpers. R401      \n*Bumpers should protect all corners. Robots are required to use Bumpers\nto protect all outside corners of the Frame Perimeter.\nFor adequate protection, at least 6 in. (~16 cm) of Bumper\nmust be placed on each side of each outside corner (see Figure 9‑3) and\nmust extend to within ¼ in. (~6 mm) of the Frame\nPerimeter corner. If a Frame Perimeter side\nis shorter than 12 in. (~31 cm), that entire FRAME PERIMETER side must be\nprotected by a Bumper (see Figure 9‑4). A\nround or circular Frame Perimeter, or segment\nof the Frame Perimeter, is considered to have\nan infinite number of corners, therefore the entire frame or frame segment must\nbe completely protected by Bumpers. Figure 9‑3 Bumper corner examples  Figure 9‑4 Bumper around full side/corner ",
